{  
  "response_text": "The series begins with a near-universal clustering of trajectories at the upper bound of the y-axis, reflecting the initial herd size per household at step 0. All simulated trials start with identical resource conditions, leading to synchronized actions among agents during the early steps. A steep, universal decline occurs across all runs within the first 20 steps as agents aggressively maximize livestock numbers, exceeding carrying capacity and triggering rapid destocking events in response to diminished pasture health. By step 40, trajectories diverge slightly around a trough approximate 42, indicating critical resource exhaustion and delayed agent adaptations.   Followed by a gradual rebound beginning at steps 50-60 in most runs as grazing pressure eases and biomass recovers, trajectories converge toward a stable band between 48 and 50 by steps 80-100. The dynamics parallel cascading resource depletion followed by behavioral recalibration, though the absence of strategy switching suggests persistent compromises between livelihood and conservation. Variance increases during the trough phase due to stochastic pasture recovery rates, but most trials show time-averaged equilibrium alignment with the resting threshold condition."  
  }

